  "prompt_type": "cognitive",
  "prompt_text": "Write a function to check if a binary tree is balanced. Define what balanced means.",
  "response_text": "To check if a binary tree is balanced, we will consider a balanced tree as one where the left and right subtrees of every node differ in height by no more than 1. Here's a Python function that performs this check:\n\n```python\ndef get_height(node):\n    if node is None:\n        return 0\n    else:\n        return 1 + max(get_height(node.left), get_height(node.right))\n\ndef is_balanced(node):\n    if node is None:\n        return True\n\n    left_height = get_height(node.left)\n    right_height = get_height(node.right)\n\n    if abs(left_height - right_height) > 1:\n        return False\n\n    return is_balanced(node.left) and is_balanced(node.right)\n\n# Example usage:\nroot = Node(1)\nroot.left = Node(2)\nroot.right = Node(3)\nroot.left.left = Node(4)\nroot.left.right = Node(5)\nroot.right.left = Node(6)\nroot.right.right = Node(7)\n\nprint(is_balanced(root))  # Output: True\n```\n\nIn this code, `get_height` calculates the height of a given node, and `is_balanced` checks if the tree is balanced based on the height difference between the left and right subtrees.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 10\nV (Verbal Fluency): 9\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 10\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 10\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 8\nF (Flexibility): 9\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
